definition.value: An elemental carbon in the form of virtually pure colloidal particles that are produced by incomplete combustion or thermal decomposition of gaseous or liquid hydrocarbons under controlled conditions. A black, finely divided pellet or powder, its properties of specific surface area, particle size and structure, conductivity and colour can be varied by varying the exact conditions for its production. It is used in tyres, rubber and plastic products, printing inks and coatings.
A penicillin in which the substituent at position 6 of the penam ring is a 2-[(4-ethyl-2,3-dioxopiperazin-1-yl)carboxamido]-2-phenylacetamido group.

A zinc atom in which the nucleus contains 35 neutrons. It has a half-life of 244 days, decaying by emission of a positron (beta(+) decay), and is the most abundant and stable of the 25 known radioisotopes of zinc.

An anionic ganglioside that is the conjugate base alpha-N-acetylneuraminosyl-(2->3)-[beta-D-galactosyl-(1->3)-N-acetyl-beta-D-galactosaminyl-(1->4)]-beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-glucosyl-(1<->1')-ceramide arising from deprotonation of the neuraminosyl carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
An elemental molecular entity in which all of the atoms have atomic number 26.
Any unsaturated fatty acid anion with one double or triple bond in the fatty acid chain.
A  hydroxy-1,4-naphthoquinone that is 1,4-naphthoquinone in which the hydrogens at positions 2 and 5 are substituted by methyl and hydroxy groups, respectively.
Any aldoxime derived from an aliphatic aldehyde.

A large family of low molecular weight compounds most commonly found in plant crown gall tumours or hairy root tumours produced by parasitic bacteria of the genus Agrobacterium. They are also found in marine invertebrates, fungi, higher plants and mammals.
A family of sphingolipids that share a common structural feature, a sphingosine base backbone.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine in which the 1- and 2-acyl groups are specified as oleoyl and palmitoyl respectively.
An N-acylsphingosine in which the acyl moiety contains 26 carbons and 1 double bond.
An antagonist that binds to and deactivates glucocorticoid receptors.
A member of the class of imidazoles that is 1-(2,4-dichlorophenyl)-2-(imidazol-1-yl)ethanol in which the hydroxyl hydrogen is replaced by a 2,4-dichlorobenzyl group.
A 1-[2-(2,4-dichlorobenzyloxy)-2-(2,4-dichlorophenyl)ethyl]imidazole that has R configuration.
A 1-[2-(2,4-dichlorobenzyloxy)-2-(2,4-dichlorophenyl)ethyl]imidazole that has S) configuration.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphate(2-) obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of 1,2-di[(4Z,7Z,10Z,13Z,16Z,19Z)]-docosahexaenoyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphate; major species at pH 7.3.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate(2-) in which the 1- and 2-acyl substituent are specified as palmitoyl and (4Z,7Z,10Z,13Z,16Z,19Z)-docosahexaenoyl respectively; major species at pH 7.3.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol in which both acyl groups are specified as palmitoyl (hexadecanoyl).
A hydroxy monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of 3-hydroxyisovaleric acid.
A Daphnia metabolite produced by the species Daphnia galeata.
An animal metabolite produced by arthropods such as crabs, lobsters, crayfish, shrimps and krill.
A medium-chain fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of dodecenoic acid.
A Daphnia metabolite produced by the species Daphnia magna.
A crustacean metabolite produced by the genus of small planktonic arthropods, Daphnia
Any salt derived from a member of the class of dithiocarbamic acids by the formal replacement of the hydrogen of the dithiocarboxy group by a metal.
An EC 1.3.5.* (oxidoreductase acting on CH-CH of donor with a quinone or related compound as acceptor) inhibitor that interferes with the action of succinate dehydrogenase (quinone), EC 1.3.5.1.
A polymyxin having a (6R)-6-methyloctanoyl group at the amino terminus.
A Daphnia metabolite produced by the species Daphnia tenebrosa.
An anionic phospholipid obtained by deprotonation of the phospho groups of any phosphatidylinositol bisphosphate; major species at pH 7.3.
An anionic phospholipid obtained by deprotonation of the phospho groups of any phosphatidylinositol trisphosphate; major species at pH 7.3.
A sphingolipid comprising an unspecified fatty acyl group attached to the nitrogen of L-erythro-sphingosine.
Any opine whose structure is based on the condensation of an amino acid with a carbohydrate or a keto-acid.
A 1-phosphatidyl-1D-myo-inositol 3,4,5-trisphosphate(7-) in which the phosphatidyl acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are specified as stearoyl and arachidonoyl respectively.
A ceramide consisting of an undefined sphingoid base linked to an undefined fatty acid via an amide bond.
A member of the class of piperidines that is N-isobutylpiperidine in which a hydrogen of one of the methyl groups is replaced by a p-tert-butylphenyl group.
A 1-[3-(4-tert-butylphenyl)-2-methylpropyl]piperidine that has R configuration.
A 1-[3-(4-tert-butylphenyl)-2-methylpropyl]piperidine that has S configuration.

A member of the class of morpholines that is 2,6-dimethylmorpholine in which the hydrogen attached to the nitrogen is replaced by a dodecyl group. The configuration at positions 2 and 6 is unknown or unspecified.

An EC 1.14.13.* (oxidoreductase acting on paired donors, incorporating 1 atom of oxygen, with NADH or NADPH as one donor) inhibitor that interferes with the action of methylsterol monooxygenase (EC 1.14.13.72).
Any compound that inhibits the biosynthesis of any sterol.
An EC 1.3.1.* (oxidoreductase acting on donor CH-CH group, NAD(+) or NADP(+) as acceptor) inhibitor that interferes with the action of Delta(14)-sterol reductase (EC 1.3.1.70).
An ester resulting from the formal condensation of the hydroxy group of an alcohol, phenol, heteroarenol, or enol with an organosulfonic acid.
A sphingomyelin d18:1 in which the ceramide N-acyl group is specified as hexacosanoyl.
A sphingomyelin in which the total number of carbons in the fatty acyl group is 26 with 1 double bond.

A member of the class of morpholines that is 2,6-dimethylmorpholine in which the hydrogen attached to the nitrogen is replaced by a tridecyl group. The configuration at positions 2 and 6 is unknown or unspecified.

A member of the class of morpholines that is 2,6-dimethylmorpholine in which the hydrogen attached to the nitrogen is replaced by an undecyl group. The configuration at positions 2 and 6 is unknown or unspecified.

A member of the class of morpholines that is 2,6-dimethylmorpholine in which the hydrogen attached to the nitrogen is replaced by a tetradecyl group. The configuration at positions 2 and 6 is unknown or unspecified.
